	affiliations = {Institute of Business Administration (IBA), Khwaja Fareed University of Engineering and Information Technology (KFUEIT), Rahim Yar Khan, Pakistan},
	abstract = {Achieving financial freedom hinges on the principle of green development, which empowers individuals to make choices free from financial constraints. This study explores the connection between financial freedom and green development, looking at how green development may help or impede achieving financial freedom. By estimating multiple aspects of green development, the study uses the Autoregressive Distributed Lag (ARDL) model period 2001 to 2023 to examine how green development affects financial independence attainment. Both immediate and equilibrium effects are captured by separating the study into short-run and long-run coefficients. Short-term findings show that the Green Index score, Goal 1 (No Poverty), Goal 7 (Affordable and Clean Energy), Goal 13 (Climate Action), and Goal 14 (Life below Water) all significantly improve financial freedom. Goals 12 (Responsible Consumption and Production) and 15 (Life on Land) suffer from detrimental effects. Financial independence has less impact in the long term, as seen by the green Index Score, and the majority of green targets only Goal 17 (Partnerships for the Goals), which has a significant positive, suggesting a possible long-term beneficial impact. The findings highlight the complexity of financial freedom's link with green development by suggesting that although short-term effects differ between green developments, the long-term implications are more subdued. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
