	affiliations = {University of Speyer and National Institute for Public Administration Germany, Speyer, Germany},
	abstract = {The contribution explores the digital regulation of the EU and its implications for administrative practices in Germany. It begins with a discussion of the evolving definition of AI, emphasizing its complexity and the challenges posed by biases in training data, which can affect the integrity of AI systems. The various application scenarios of AI in German administrations, including public safety, social benefits allocation and environmental monitoring are highlighted, illustrating the potential benefits and risks associated with these technologies. The essay also examines the legal framework governing use of AI in German public administrations, noting diverse procedural regulations across federal states and the implications of automated decision-making. It discusses recent legislative efforts to modernize tax procedures and to ensure transparency in automated processes while addressing concerns about citizen participation and data protection under GDPR. It emphasizes the need for robust guarantees to protect citizens’ rights in an increasingly algorithm-driven administrative landscape, advocating balance between efficiency and participatory governance. This critical analysis of how EU digital regulations are shaping AI deployment in Germany highlights the opportunities and challenges for future governance. © The Author(s), under exclusive license to Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2025.},
