	affiliations = {Manipal University Jaipur, Rajasthan, Jaipur, India; DES-MDRC, Panjab University, Punjab, Chandigarh, India; Smt. A.A.A. Govt. P.G. College, Haryana, Kalka, India},
	abstract = {This study conducts a systematic literature review of 180 publications to critically evaluate the evolving field of green finance and its role in advancing sustainable development. Employing the Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic Reviews and Meta-Analyses protocol, the review synthesizes research across conceptual foundations, financial instruments, geographical contexts, technological mediations, and behavioral-normative dimensions. The findings reveal that while green finance has gained significant traction as a mechanism for aligning capital markets with ecological imperatives, the field remains constrained by definitional ambiguity, empirical fragmentation, and normative tensions. Green bonds, environmental, social, and governance portfolios, and climate funds dominate the literature, yet evidence of their dual mandate, financial returns, and ecological effectiveness remains inconclusive. Geographically, scholarship is disproportionately concentrated in Europe and North America, leaving the Global South underrepresented despite its acute climate vulnerabilities. Emerging technologies such as blockchain and artificial intelligence are celebrated as enhancers of transparency and efficiency, but their paradoxical ecological and ethical implications remain insufficiently interrogated. Moreover, behavioral and cultural factors, as well as issues of equity and environmental justice, are marginalized within the discourse. The review concludes by identifying key research gaps and advancing a second-generation research agenda that is integrative, context-sensitive, technologically critical, and normatively reflexive. © 2026 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.},
