	abstract = {The past several years have seen widespread adoption of artificial intelligence (AI) by tax administrations, bringing with it both potential benefits and risks. If employed effectively, AI could improve the efficiency of fraud detection and tax audits, provide better advice for taxpayers and strengthen tax authorities’ compliance with the law. However, these same developments raise concerns regarding privacy violations, lack of transparency, and potential discrimination. Adoption of AI risks undermining accountability and transparency in tax administration, facilitating invasive surveillance of taxpayers, and subjecting taxpayers to decisions that cannot be explained or evaluated in terms of procedural fairness. As AI tools become widespread, this will require rethinking of taxpayer’s rights and tax authorities’ legal obligations. © The Editors and Contributors Severally 2025. All rights reserved.},
