	doi = {10.22507/rli.v22n2a3896},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105030724073?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Docente de la Facultad de Ciencias Económicas Administrativas y Contables, Universidad Libre, seccional Barranquilla, Colombia; Corporación Universitaria Remington, Colombia; Directora del Fondo Editorial de la Universidad Doctor José Gregorio Hernández, Colombia; Magíster en Ingeniería de Computación y Sistemas, Contador público, Decano de la Facultad de Contabilidad de la Universidad Nacional del Centro del Perú, Peru},
	abstract = {Introduction. This research analyzes the impact of generative artificial intelligence (AI) on tax administration between 2021 and 2025, focusing on how this technology has transformed operational efficiency, institutional transparency, and equity in the relationship between taxpayers and tax authorities. In a context of accelerated digital transformation, the study examines the scope and limitations of tax automation from technical, regulatory, and social perspectives. Objective. To identify the advances, challenges, and implications resulting from the implementation of intelligent systems in tax management, with special attention to management auditing, assisted decisionmaking, and organizational sustainability. Materials and Methods. The methodology is based on a qualitative documentary review, involving the analysis of scientific articles, technical reports, and case studies published between 2020 and 2024. A hermeneutic approach was used to interpret the implications of AI from an interdisciplinary perspective. Results. Among the results, improvements are highlighted in fraud detection, the reduction of human errors, the optimization of tax analysis, and the redefinition of professional roles. At the same time, ethical challenges are identified related to algorithmic transparency, personal data protection, fairness in automated decision-making, and the institutional digital divide. Conclusions. Artificial intelligence has generated structural transformations in the tax domain, enhancing operational and analytical capacities. Its effective use, however, requires adaptive legal frameworks, ongoing training, and technological governance aligned with principles of fiscal justice and public oversight. © (2025), (Corporacion Universitaria Lasallista). All right reserved.},
	author_keywords = {administración tributaria; administração tributária; Artificial Intelligence; auditoria fiscal; auditoría fiscal; Digital Transformation; equidad tributaria; equidade tributária; inteligencia artificial; inteligência artificial; Tax Administration; Tax Auditing; Tax Equity; transformación digital; transformação digital},
