	affiliations = {Department of Accounting, University of Cape Coast, Cape Coast, Ghana; Department of Accounting, University of Cape Coast (UCC), Cape Coast, Ghana},
	abstract = {The field of wealth management and financial planning is changing as a result of the quick development of automation and artificial intelligence (AI). The field has changed from being primarily driven by human expertise to becoming a data-centric ecosystem that is fuelled by big data analytics, machine learning, and behavioural finance models. From asset allocation and retirement planning to portfolio design, AI-enabled robo-advisors now offer automated, objective, affordable, and customized financial solutions. The revolutionary role of AI in democratizing investment management and facilitating highly customized financial services is examined in this chapter. While critically evaluating important issues like data privacy, the ethical application of AI, algorithmic transparency, and regulatory compliance, it emphasizes the integration of algorithms in risk modelling, portfolio optimization, and real-time decision assistance. Although robo-advisory platforms provide access to investment services and promote financial inclusiveness, worries about algorithmic bias, the decline of human judgement, and an excessive reliance on automated decision-making tools still exist. The chapter concludes that a balanced strategy is needed to maintain technological efficiency while preserving ethical norms, accountability, and regulatory compliance to implement AI in financial planning in a sustainable manner. © 2026 selection and editorial matter, Syed Hasan Jafar, Hemachandran K, Donkor Nawaah, Raul Villamarin Rodriguez; individual chapters, the contributors.},
